9.body: How was your weekend? Do anything fun or interesting?

12.body: Ohhh, nice
I realllllllly liked Innsbruck, Austria. The scenery was gorgeous! What about you?
I liked Athens a lot. I'm a history nerd and loved Greek mythology growing up.
I'd enjoy that. Maybe we can go to this best spot in town for tacos that you evidently know about?
When is yours?
Ugh, not soon enough. I can't really decide what I want my next trip to be though, which is slowing things down a bit
Nice. Where are you going?
So, I'm going to say location dependent for driving haha

So, technically, I'm pretty sure the area inside an international airport isn't "in the country". You're not in the country until you clear customs. So, I definitely say that if you don't leave the airport, you weren't really in the country.
Louisiana, Arkansas, Mississippi, Minnesota, Wisconsin, North Dakota. So, guess it's 6 haha
So do you count it as you having been in Russia, just that you haven't seen Russia?
Anyways, I recently got back into playing soccer a lot. Snowboarding in the winter. My nerdier interests are guitar, programming, and tech
I had a 2 hour layover there on my way to Germany a few years ago, but I never left the airport. So, idk if that really counts as having been there
What'd you like about Mykonos?
Idk where I'm going to go yet. Might so domestic. I have 5 of the 48 states I haven't been in yet and am thinking of working on crossing those off
Technically, I think I've been to Iceland, but I don't really count it. It looks like you're landing on another planet when you land though. It's pretty crazy.
Where'd you go in Greece?
Driving through though. Hmm. I mean, if you drive across the state of Kansas but never get out of the car, I'm pretty sure you saw most of what there is to see in Kansas 🤪
I rented a quad and drove it pretty much all over the island as my only form of entertainment haha
I have haha. I've been to Athens, which I liked a lot, Santorini, and Paros. What'd you think of Athens and Santorini?

Oddly, I wouldn't list travel as something that I'm all that into. I'm super curious and love exploring new places, ideas, etc. but to me, idk if that ever translated into "likes to travel" in my head. Hmm...

Hey, I'm really sorry for dissapearing for a month. I had an extremely unexpected family emergency that resulted in me basically moving to Harrisburg for three weeks and then I started a new job and grad school. I'm back in Philadelphia now, settled in, and I'd still be up for grabbing those tacos, but I totally understand if that ship has sailed.
What are you doing in Iceland? Have you been there before?
Haha I like traveling, I just think I call it "exploring". I've been trying to learn how to cook. It's been... an adventure. Maybe you could teach me!
Santorini did have really cool views, that I got bored of after like 1.5 days. That place seems like it's manufactured specifically to be a romantic couples retreat
What are you into?
And yeah I was on Santorini for like 3 days 🤦‍♂️

Companies will issue non-traded financial instruments to raise capital, to give to employees as a form of compensation, for risk management purposes, etc. The existence of the instrument basically results in the company having a liability that they may have to fulfill at some point in the future. Financial reporting standards require that these companies report the value of the instruments on their financial statements upon issuance and then update that value periodically (usually quarterly). So, the companies hire a third party to value the instrument for them. I work for the third party and the number I come up with gets put on the company's financial statements.
